Date: March 2026

# INTRO  WHY THIS RESEARCH MATTERS FOR IMAGE FOUNDRY

This report expands beyond the CGI and visualisation sector to look at how the wider world of creative agencies — branding studios, advertising agencies, motion design houses, digital experience agencies — position themselves online and on their landing pages.

The rationale is straightforward: the most creative agencies in the world bring genuine invention to how they sell themselves, not just to how they do their work. Studying their approach yields insights that purely technical or sector-specific analysis cannot. They experiment with positioning language, with structure, with the relationship between copy and portfolio, and with what it means to attract the right client rather than simply the most clients.

Every agency profiled in this report has a live URL link embedded so you can visit and review each page directly. The URLs are also collected in a reference table at the back.

| *“The best creative agency websites don’t just tell you what the agency does — they demonstrate it. The writing is the craft. The structure is the thinking. The restraint is the confidence.”* — Observation from this research |
| --- |

# 01  SIX POSITIONING MODELS USED BY GREAT CREATIVE AGENCIES

Across the agencies reviewed, six distinct strategic models emerge for how creative studios position themselves on their homepages. Each has trade-offs. Understanding them will help Image Foundry choose the model most appropriate to its audience, ambition, and existing evidence base.

| **THEME 1  ****The Commercial Proof Model — outcomes speak louder than craft** |
| --- |

The boldest and most commercially sophisticated approach. Rather than describing the service, the homepage leads entirely with what the work achieved for clients — measured in hard business metrics. Work descriptions are replaced by result statements. Testimonials are replaced by numbers.

Ragged Edge (raggededge.com) is the purest example. Every project on the homepage follows a rigid formula:

| **RAGGED EDGE HOMEPAGE FORMULA** *“[Brand] committed to [something meaningful]. With a rebrand [that achieved something]. [Specific metric].”* |
| --- |

In practice this reads as: “Wise committed to the world’s money. With a rebrand rolled out in 175 countries. 58% share price increase in 12 months after launch.” Or: “Marshmallow committed to insuring difference. With a rebrand that backs the exceptions to the rules. $2 billion valuation in 2025.”

This model requires something most studios are reluctant to do: ask clients for commercial outcome data and then lead with it. But the conversion effect is significant — it turns a portfolio showcase into a business case.

What Image Foundry can take from this: Begin tracking and collecting commercial outcome data from clients (off-plan units sold, time to sell, e-commerce conversion rate changes, product launch results). Even one or two strong metrics, displayed consistently, could anchor an entire homepage.

| **THEME 2  ****The Provocation Model — filter clients with your opinions** |
| --- |

Some of the best agencies use their homepage to make an argument, not just a pitch. The headline is a point of view, not a description of services. The goal is not to appeal to everyone — it is to deeply resonate with the specific kind of client who shares that worldview, and to quietly repel everyone else.

Ragged Edge opens with: “Never be the same again.” Beneath it: “Radged Edge is a brand company for people who refuse to settle for average. It’s time to commit to a different reality.”

Made Thought (madethought.com) opens with: “BEAUTIFULLY BOLD FUTURES” and their positioning statement reads: “WE BUILD BRANDS THAT DEFY CONVENTION AND CHANGE THE CONVERSATION.”

Dawn Creative (dawncreative.co.uk) opens with: “Your brand is a sleeping giant. Let’s wake it up.” This is softer provocation — it challenges the prospect’s current state without being confrontational, and it positions the agency as the activating force.

What Image Foundry can take from this: A mild provocation can be powerful — particularly for the product manufacturer audience who may still be using photography for everything. “Your product deserves better than a photoshoot” is an opinionated statement that will resonate with the right prospect and qualify out the wrong one.

| **THEME 3  ****The Ambition Alignment Model — signal who your ideal client is** |
| --- |

A subtler approach: use the positioning language to reflect the aspirations of the ideal client back at them. Rather than describing capabilities, describe the kind of companies you serve — and make those companies feel that working with you is consistent with their own self-image.

Koto (koto.com): “We make ambitious ideas for ambitious brands.” The repetition of “ambitious” tells Microsoft, Amazon, Google and Tripadvisor (all Koto clients) that this is a studio that operates at their level. It also signals to smaller or less confident brands that they may not be the right fit.

Human Agency (humanagency.com): “Harnessing the power of our agency so you can fully exercise yours.” The wordplay on “agency” (the company name + the concept of autonomy) creates an identity statement that speaks directly to founders and leaders with big ideas. Their tagline: “You have a right to agency, we’re here to advance it.”

Instrument (instrument.com): “We’re a digital-first design agency working at the intersection of creativity and technology.” Then immediately: a client list that includes Nike, Google, Netflix, Spotify, Pinterest, Microsoft, Patagonia, Uber, Marriott, Instagram, Sephora, NBA, Nordstrom, Stripe, Salesforce, Levi’s, PayPal. The ambition is signalled entirely through the client roster.

What Image Foundry can take from this: Who are the clients that Image Foundry most wants to work with? The language should make those clients feel this studio was made for them. For property: “London’s most ambitious developers trust us to sell what isn’t built yet.” For product: “For brands who are done with photoshoots.”

| **THEME 4  ****The Manifesto Model — the homepage as belief system, not shop window** |
| --- |

A growing number of premium creative agencies are deliberately moving away from the homepage-as-portfolio model and towards the homepage-as-worldview. They are not trying to show you everything they can do. They are trying to show you who they are.

DixonBaxi, one of London’s most respected brand studios, launched a new site in 2025 with this stated philosophy from co-founder Simon Dixon: “It’s not a shop window. It’s a space to share the thinking and ethos that drive us. You’ll find our work, but more importantly, what shapes it. No guff. Just us.”

Further (formerly DesignStudio) opens with: “A bet on the future. A belief in human creativity.” There is no service description above the fold. No client list. Just a statement of conviction, followed by a high-quality portfolio. Clients include UFC, Squarespace, Eurostar, Airbnb, Apple TV+, Xbox and the Royal Ballet.

This model works when the studio’s reputation precedes it — when visitors already know who you are and the homepage’s job is to confirm the quality and character of the work, not explain what the studio does. It requires a very strong portfolio to carry the page.

What Image Foundry can take from this: This model is aspirational for a growing studio. Elements of it — a convictions statement, an editorial tone, a strong single hero visual — can be incorporated into a more conversion-oriented structure without fully committing to the manifesto approach.

| **THEME 5  ****The In-House Craft Model — everything happens here, nothing is outsourced** |
| --- |

Some agencies make their primary differentiator the seamlessness of their production — the fact that strategy, creative, and execution all happen under one roof. This is particularly compelling for clients who have been burned by fragmented agency relationships.

Stink Studios (stinkstudios.com): “We’re a global creative studio. From the thinking to the making, it all happens in-house.”

This is a clear, confident response to a specific client anxiety: “Will I have to manage multiple vendors?” The answer is given before the question is asked. The subtitle “From the thinking to the making” creates a start-to-finish image of creative ownership.

Dawn Creative (dawncreative.co.uk) positions similarly across three service pillars — Brand, Digital and Motion — with a consistent “one studio, everything you need” message. Their service menu is presented as integrated, not modular.

What Image Foundry can take from this: If Image Foundry handles everything from briefing to final file delivery without outsourcing, this is worth saying explicitly. “From your CAD drawings to finished marketing imagery — all produced in our studio, by our team” addresses the process anxiety that many first-time CGI buyers feel.

| **THEME 6  ****The Platform-for-Thinking Model — opinion content builds authority** |
| --- |

Several of the best agencies use editorial content on their homepage not just to fill space but as a positioning signal. The kind of thinking an agency publishes tells you as much about its sophistication as the portfolio does. Prospects who read an agency’s published opinions before contacting them are considerably warmer leads.

Koto (koto.com) publishes thought leadership under “Studio News” with pieces like “Some UK brands are tired — Koto’s James Greenfield on branding today” and “The femtech positioning problem.” These are not service pitches — they are arguments that attract a certain kind of client.

Dawn Creative publishes a regular “morning digest” blog covering topics like “The Dos and Don’ts of Motion Design in 2026” and “10 Common SEO Mistakes.” This builds search traffic and demonstrates expertise beyond portfolio shots.

Instrument (instrument.com) publishes articles with titles like “Modern Brand Should Feel Alive: Your Brand Isn’t a File. It’s a Dynamic System” — opinionated, forward-looking, and designed to attract brand leaders who think about these things.

What Image Foundry can take from this: Even 4–6 well-written pieces of editorial content on topics like “Why CGI outperforms photography for kitchen product launches” or “What developers get wrong about pre-construction marketing imagery” would build authority, improve search visibility, and demonstrate that Image Foundry thinks strategically about its work.

# 02  HEADLINE PATTERNS — WHAT THESE AGENCIES ACTUALLY SAY

The following is a curated reference of real homepage headlines and positioning statements from the agencies reviewed, grouped by type. Every headline is shown verbatim with analysis of the structural technique being used and a live link to the page.

## 2.1  The Conviction Statement

A bold, present-tense belief that defines the agency’s reason for existing. Not descriptive — declarative.

| **HEADLINE** | **AGENCY + LINK** | **TECHNIQUE** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ***“Never be the same again”*** | [Ragged Edge](https://raggededge.com/) | Command. Impossible to misread. Filters for ambition. |
| ***“A bet on the future. A belief in human creativity.”*** | [Further (DesignStudio)](https://www.further.group/) | Two short sentences. Rhythm. Opposites (bet/belief) create tension and interest. |
| ***“BEAUTIFULLY BOLD FUTURES”*** | [Made Thought](https://www.madethought.com/) | Three capitalised words. No verb. The ambiguity is the point — it applies to the work AND to the client’s brand. |
| ***“WE BUILD BRANDS THAT DEFY CONVENTION AND CHANGE THE CONVERSATION.”*** | [Made Thought](https://www.madethought.com/) | Full caps. Both verbs (defy, change) are active and contrarian. Attracts challengers, repels followers. |

## 2.2  The Transformation Frame

Positions the prospect before and after working with the studio. Acknowledges the current state and promises a different future.

| **HEADLINE** | **AGENCY + LINK** | **TECHNIQUE** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ***“Your brand is a sleeping giant. Let’s wake it up.”*** | [Dawn Creative](https://www.dawncreative.co.uk/) | ‘Giant’ flatters the prospect. ‘Sleeping’ implies untapped potential. ‘Let’s’ makes it collaborative, not prescriptive. |
| ***“Harnessing the power of our agency so you can fully exercise yours.”*** | [Human Agency](https://www.humanagency.com/) | Double meaning on ‘agency’ (the studio + the concept of autonomy). Positions the client as empowered, not dependent. |
| ***“We move brands forward. Faster, smarter, and with purpose.”*** | [Dawn Creative](https://www.dawncreative.co.uk/) | Three adverbs (faster, smarter, purpose) in ascending order of depth. Momentum implied in ‘forward’. |

## 2.3  The Identity + Descriptor

Simple, clear self-identification followed by a sharp description of the offer. Prioritises clarity and confidence over cleverness.

| **HEADLINE** | **AGENCY + LINK** | **TECHNIQUE** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ***“We make ambitious ideas for ambitious brands.”*** | [Koto](https://koto.com/) | Chiastic structure — same qualifier both sides. ‘Ambitious’ repeated does the client-selection work elegantly. |
| ***“We’re a global creative studio. From the thinking to the making, it all happens in-house.”*** | [Stink Studios](https://www.stinkstudios.com/) | Part 1: what we are. Part 2: the differentiator (in-house, end to end). Resolves the outsourcing anxiety immediately. |
| ***“We’re a digital-first design agency working at the intersection of creativity and technology.”*** | [Instrument](https://www.instrument.com/) | ‘Digital-first’ is a positioning qualifier that tells clients what to expect. ‘Intersection’ is doing the differentiation work. |
| ***“We visualise, energise ******&****** humanise Products, Places ******&****** Spaces.”*** | [Urban3D](https://urban3d.net/) | Triple verb rhythm creates energy and memorability. Each verb escalates the emotional value (technical → dynamic → human). |

# 03  ANNOTATED AGENCY PROFILES — WITH LIVE LINKS

Each profile below analyses the agency’s homepage as a landing page — assessing its structure, copy, visual approach, social proof strategy, CTA, and what a studio like Image Foundry can learn from it. All URLs are live and clickable.

## 3.1  Ragged Edge

| **URL** | [raggededge.com](https://raggededge.com/) |
| --- | --- |
| **Type** | Brand strategy & identity agency, London & New York |
| **Clients** | Wise, Marshmallow, Papier, ZOE, Globe-Trotter, Palmetto, Omlet, Solflare, Tilt, Eager |
| **Hero Headline** | “Never be the same again” — five words, no punctuation, no verb after the first word |
| **Sub-positioning** | “Radged Edge is a brand company for people who refuse to settle for average. It’s time to commit to a different reality.” |
| **Page Structure** | Headline → repeating project tiles (each with brand name + commitment + metric) → opinion content → job listing → contact |
| **Primary CTA** | “Partnerships” (in nav — not a conversion CTA in the traditional sense; relies on reputation and referrals to drive inbound) |
| **Social Proof Method** | OUTCOME METRICS, not testimonials. Every project tile includes a specific commercial result: 58% share price increase (Wise), $2B valuation (Marshmallow), 40% revenue increase (Globe-Trotter), 92% follower growth (Palmetto), 70% higher CTR on Meta (Tilt) |
| **Visual Style** | Clean, minimal, typographically strong. High-quality brand imagery per project. No dark backgrounds — the work creates the drama. Cases shown in vertical 4:5 portrait tiles. |
| **What makes it exceptional** | The consistent application of the ‘committed to + outcome metric’ formula transforms the portfolio from a showcase into a business case. There is no way to read this homepage without understanding that this agency moves commercial needles, not just aesthetics. The brevity of the headline leaves room for the work to speak. |
| **What could be improved** | No traditional CTA for inbound enquiries — works for an agency that relies on referrals but would underperform if receiving cold paid traffic. No process description for prospects who are unfamiliar with brand agency engagements. |
| **Conversion Score** | 9/10 for reputation-led inbound. 6/10 for cold paid traffic. |
| **Key lesson for Image Foundry** | Attach a specific business metric to every portfolio case. “We produced the CGI for this development. It sold 80% of units off-plan within 90 days.” That sentence is worth more than any amount of production description. |

## 3.2  Koto

| **URL** | [koto.com](https://koto.com/) |
| --- | --- |
| **Type** | International creative agency — brand identity, strategy, digital. London, New York, LA, Berlin, Sydney. |
| **Clients** | Microsoft Copilot+PC, Amazon, Google/Fitbit, Tripadvisor |
| **Hero Headline** | “We’re Koto / The Creative Company / We make ambitious ideas for ambitious brands.” |
| **Sub-positioning** | “Five offices, one studio, united by optimism, collaboration, and craft.” |
| **Page Structure** | Headline + showreel button → project grid with case study descriptions → studio news/editorial → contact (email addresses by location) |
| **Primary CTA** | No single CTA button. Navigation has: Our work │ Studio news │ Contact. The work carries the conversion weight. |
| **Social Proof Method** | Client brand names (Microsoft, Amazon, Google) function as social proof by association. Case study descriptions explain the strategic challenge and solution — framed as partnership narratives, not just deliverables. |
| **Visual Style** | Clean, considered, restrained. The work is the dominant visual. Typography is precise and modern. Light background. High information density in case study text. |
| **What makes it exceptional** | The case study copy is unusually well-written. Rather than describing what Koto made, it describes the strategic challenge: “For 25 years Tripadvisor has been the world’s travel companion... but in a race to compete with booking engines on price and capacity, the brand risked losing its edge.” This frames every project as a business problem solved, not a visual exercise. |
| **What could be improved** | No explicit CTA for new business enquiries above the fold. No testimonials — relies entirely on the reputation of the client names. Would not convert well for cold traffic. |
| **Conversion Score** | 8/10 for known-studio inbound. 5/10 for cold paid traffic. |
| **Key lesson for Image Foundry** | Write case study copy that describes the client’s commercial challenge before describing the creative solution. “This developer needed to sell 200 units off-plan in a competitive Manchester market before construction began.” Then tell them how the CGI solved it. |

## 3.3  Stink Studios

| **URL** | [stinkstudios.com](https://www.stinkstudios.com/) |
| --- | --- |
| **Type** | Global creative studio — advertising, digital experiences, branding |
| **Clients** | Canva, HOKA, Riot Games (League of Legends) |
| **Hero Headline** | “We’re a global creative studio. From the thinking to the making, it all happens in-house.” |
| **Page Structure** | Headline + showreel → project grid (with sector tags: Advertising / Digital / Branding) → news / press mentions → contact |
| **Primary CTA** | Contact (in navigation). No conversion form above the fold. |
| **Social Proof Method** | Press: “AdAge lists our HOKA campaign in their ‘creative campaigns to know’.” Sector-credible client names. |
| **Visual Style** | Dark, editorial, minimal. The projects are shown as large, full-bleed tiles that demonstrate craft rather than explain services. Strong use of typography at scale. |
| **What makes it exceptional** | The two-sentence positioning is nearly perfect. Sentence 1 (identity) + Sentence 2 (differentiator) covers everything a prospect needs to know above the fold. ‘From thinking to making, in-house’ is a complete value proposition compressed into 8 words. |
| **What could be improved** | No outcomes or metrics. Heavy reliance on the recognisability of client names for credibility. The dark aesthetic, while effective for brand positioning, may reduce readability for copy-heavy zones on mobile. |
