| **Key lesson for Image Foundry** | The repeated, warm CTA (‘Let’s talk’) is worth considering as an alternative to ‘Get a quote’ or ‘Book a call’. It reduces commitment anxiety while still initiating the conversation. |

# 04  STRUCTURAL PATTERNS — WHAT THE BEST PAGES HAVE IN COMMON

Looking across all agencies reviewed — both the creative agency set in this report and the CGI/visualisation set from the original report — a set of structural principles emerge that are consistent among the highest-converting pages regardless of sector or aesthetic.

## 4.1  The Work IS the Above-the-Fold Visual

Without exception, the best agency pages use a real piece of client work as the primary above-the-fold visual — not a stock image, not an abstract graphic, not a studio photo. The work does the selling before a single word is read. This is even more important for a visual studio like Image Foundry than it is for a strategy or advertising agency.

## 4.2  The Case Study Formula That Converts

The most effective pages frame portfolio work as solved problems, not produced assets. The structure that appears most consistently across the best pages is:

- [Client] faced [specific commercial challenge or opportunity]

- [Studio] created [brief description of the work] to [solve it]

- [Specific, measurable outcome]

Ragged Edge applies this most rigidly. Koto applies it with more editorial depth. Either approach outperforms the common alternative of simply showing an image with a caption that says ‘Brand Identity for X.’

## 4.3  The Social Proof Hierarchy

Reviewing all agencies, social proof falls into a clear hierarchy of persuasive power:

| **RANK** | **SOCIAL PROOF TYPE** | **WHY IT WORKS** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **1** | **Specific commercial outcome metrics** | Numbers are objective. “58% share price increase” is inarguable. Ragged Edge’s approach. |
| **2** | **Named testimonials with job titles and company** | Specific, named, verifiable. North Made and Dawn Creative do this well. |
| **3** | **Recognisable client logos / names** | Arko London, Instrument, Koto. Works only if the names mean something to the prospect. |
| **4** | **Press / awards mentions** | Stink Studios (AdAge). Eleven (CGArchitect, Dezeen). Third-party validation but weaker than direct proof. |
| **5** | **Generic star ratings or ‘trusted by X clients’** | The weakest form for a premium service. Carries almost no persuasion weight for B2B decision-makers. |

## 4.4  CTA Language Patterns Across All Agencies

The following is a synthesis of CTA language across all agencies reviewed. Two clear camps emerge:

| **RELATIONAL CTAs (higher premium agencies)** | **TRANSACTIONAL CTAs (higher-volume, lower-commitment)** |
| --- | --- |
| “Let’s talk” — Human Agency “Get in touch” — Dawn Creative, Further “Contact Us” — Arko London, Koto “Tell us about your project” — North Made “Partnerships” — Ragged Edge (nav link) | “Get a Quote” — Ocean CGI, RealRender3D “Request a Free Sample” — product CGI studios “Book a Discovery Call” — broad service agencies “Download slide deck” — North Made (lead magnet) |
| *Suits reputation-led studios. Lower friction. More aligned with premium B2B relationship sales.* | *Suits paid traffic and cold inbound. More measurable. Requires clear value exchange (free sample, quote, call).* |

Recommendation for Image Foundry: Use transactional CTAs for paid landing pages (‘Request a Free CGI Sample’, ‘Book a Discovery Call’). Use relational CTAs on the main studio website (‘Let’s talk about your project’, ‘Tell us what you’re building’).

# 05  SYNTHESIS — WHAT IMAGE FOUNDRY SHOULD BORROW AND WHY

The following is a direct synthesis of the most transferable ideas from the broader creative agency research into specific, actionable recommendations for Image Foundry.

## 5.1  Borrow the Ragged Edge Outcome Formula for Case Studies

| **THE FORMULA** *“[Brand/Developer] committed to [aspiration]. With [what you did]. [Specific commercial result].”* |
| --- |

Applied to Image Foundry:

- "Riverside Quarter committed to selling premium apartments before foundation work began. With a full suite of CGI exterior and interior visuals produced in 12 working days. 85% of Phase 1 sold off-plan within 6 weeks of launch."

- "[Kitchen Brand] committed to launching 6 colourways simultaneously. With CGI imagery from a single 3D model. Every product image consistent, on-brand, and delivered in 10 days — with zero photoshoots."

Even one or two examples written in this format would transform the credibility of the Image Foundry portfolio section.

## 5.2  Borrow the Stink Studios Two-Part Positioning Structure

| **THE STRUCTURE** *“Part 1: Identity (who you are). Part 2: The differentiator (what makes you different from everyone else who does what you do).”* |
| --- |

For Image Foundry:

| *“"We’re a CGI and product visualisation studio. From your drawings and specifications to finished marketing-ready imagery — everything produced in-house, to deadline."”* — Example A — In-house/end-to-end differentiator |
| --- |

| *“"We’re a CGI studio that’s worked in property and product visualisation for 20+ years. We know what makes a buyer stop scrolling and a developer trust the vision."”* — Example B — Experience/expertise differentiator |
| --- |

## 5.3  Borrow the Dawn Creative Warmth + Confidence Tone

Dawn Creative proves that being opinionated and being approachable are not opposites. “Hell-bent on helping you shine” is confident language that still puts the client’s success at the centre. Their testimonials section is similarly warm — clients don’t just say the work was good, they describe what it felt like to work with the team.

Image Foundry landing page copy should feel expert but human. Not: “We utilise advanced photorealistic rendering pipelines to produce bespoke CGI assets.” Instead: “We make your property or product look real before it exists — and we make the whole process simple.”

## 5.4  Borrow the Koto Case Study Narrative Structure

Rather than captioning portfolio images with just a project name and sector, write a 2–3 sentence narrative that names the strategic challenge before describing the creative response. This builds perceived expertise and helps the prospect self-identify (“That’s exactly our situation”).

Instead of: “CGI Imagery — [Developer Name], Manchester 2025”

Write: “This Manchester developer needed marketing-ready visuals for a 200-unit scheme before planning was confirmed. We produced exterior CGIs, interior lifestyle scenes and a full suite of brochure imagery within 14 working days of receiving the plans.”

## 5.5  Consider a Contained Editorial Section

Dawn Creative, Koto and Instrument all publish regular editorial content as part of their positioning strategy. Even 4–6 well-written, opinionated pieces per year — published on the studio site and shared via LinkedIn — would build authority, drive search traffic, and give prospects a reason to return to the site before making contact.

Suggested topics for Image Foundry:

- "Why property developers who use CGI sell faster — and what the data says"

- "Why CGI for kitchen and bathroom brands costs less than photography (and delivers more)"

- "What your CGI brief should include — and what to leave out"

- "Off-plan sales and the imagery that makes the difference: a developer’s guide"

